Donny Widjaja wrote:

&gt; Hi all,
&gt; 
&gt; I am writing a few test cases to ensure that my code is throwing the
&gt; right exception.
&gt; 
&gt; The following is my test case to catch the FileNotFoundException:
&gt; 
&gt; // Read from a non existing file
&gt; public void testReadResponseFrom_Non_Existing_File() {
&gt;   try {
&gt;     TestXMLProcessor testProcessor = new TestXMLProcessor();
&gt; 
&gt;     String sNonExistingFilename = &quot;NonExisting.xml&quot;;               
&gt;     testProcessor.readResponseFromFile(sNonExistingFilename);
&gt;          
&gt;   } catch (Exception e) {
&gt;     assertEquals(FileNotFoundException.class, e.getClass());
&gt;   }
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; How can I modify my code to use the &quot;ExceptionTestCase&quot; class from
&gt; JUnit?  Can I use the &quot;ExceptionTestCase&quot; for catching exception
&gt; during unit test?

You can, but even Kent Beck himself admitted that ExceptionTestCase is 
worse than the usual pattern. (I agree with him.)

By the way, you could rewrite that test more simply if you follow the 
standard pattern.

